      {
         "id": "SECTION_prerequisites",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><span id=\"htAgeMsg\"></span></p><p><span id=\"htAmericaAbyaYalaMsg\"></span> (<htcite0>).</p><p style=\"font-style: italic;\" id=\"htChinaZhongguo\"></p><p style=\"font-style: italic;\" id=\"htJapanNipponNihonKoku\"></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "160fb48c-1711-491e-a1aa-e1257e7889af",
                     "text": "Porto-Gonçalves, Carlos Walter",
                     "page": "pp. 39-43",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2011",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nIn this, we will continue learning about different ways of representing the numbers we use to count. This time, we will get to know the Soroban (算盤), developed in Japan (Nippon koku ou Nihon koku, 日本国).\n\nTo better understand it, we recommend studying the previous texts (<htcite0>; <htcite1>) before proceeding.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9618a83e-f232-49db-84f6-fc3455a3f1d1",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Drawing to Count",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "648fb7b4-ba73-452e-980b-6d68d57d16b9",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Our actual number",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nIn the previous texts, we learned that Indigenous peoples of the Americas (*Abya Yala*) possibly used their own bodies to create different ways of counting.\n\nIn another text from History Tracers, we studied that some Indigenous peoples of the Americas (*Abya Yala*) share common ancestors with some Japanese people, despite having lived apart for a long period of time (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9ba61aa2-28ec-4667-b7af-5a4076f865dd",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Jōmon Period (縄文)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: There as Here</b><br /><br />Do you think that the Japanese could also have created instruments to represent counting, such as the yupana (<htcite0>; <htcite1>)?<br /><br />Would these conclusions have influenced each other, or were they discovered independently?</div></div></center>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9ba61aa2-28ec-4667-b7af-5a4076f865dd",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Jōmon Period (縄文)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
