      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_origin",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Origin\n\nRegarding the origin of the tool we will study, the soroban (算盤) (**Figura 1**) (<htcite0>), there is no consensus on which people were the first to develop a calculation tool, also popularly known as the abacus. It may have emerged in different places independently or originated in a single place, spreading through trade (<htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "8ab7ebef-41db-4f2b-a3e3-3530e7ff29d3",
                     "text": "Shigetoshi Oyabu",
                     "page": "fl. 14",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1842",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "88d236e3-7db4-4085-848e-0346101e6e51",
                     "text": "Samoly, K.",
                     "page": "pp. 59 - 61",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2012",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgTohoku\" src=\"\" class=\"imgcenter\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgTohoku', '0%')\" /><b>Figura 1</b>: Shigetoshi Oyabu. Preserved by the Tohoku University Main Library (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "8ab7ebef-41db-4f2b-a3e3-3530e7ff29d3",
                     "text": "Shigetoshi Oyabu",
                     "page": "fl. 14",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1842",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Despite the different possible origins, there is consensus that the soroban (算盤) arrived in Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国) from China (Zhongguo, 中國), with the Chinese model (suanpan, 算盤) being somewhat different (<htcite0>).\n\nRegarding the possible connection between how the Incas possibly used the yupana (<htcite1>) and the use of the soroban (算盤), there is no evidence of contact between these peoples; thus, it is assumed that the development of these tools occurred independently.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "88d236e3-7db4-4085-848e-0346101e6e51",
                     "text": "Samoly, K.",
                     "page": "pp. 60 - 61",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2012",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
